<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1934-01-16T15:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1934-01-16T15:00:00-05:00" n="213" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d213">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">816.01/363: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Minister in Costa Rica</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Sack</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Acting Secretary of
                                    State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">San
                                        José</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1934-01-16T14:00:00-06:00">January 16, 1934—2
                                p.m.</date><lb/>[Received 4:47 p.m.]</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>3. In accordance with suggestions contained in your telegram No. 1,
                            January 12, 5 p.m.,<note n="9" xml:id="d213fn9">See footnote 6, <ref target="#pg_225">p. 225</ref>.</note> I had occasion today to
                            informally discuss Central <pb facs="0297" n="231" xml:id="pg_231"/>
                            American developments with President Jimenez and Foreign Minister
                            Pacheco. Both expressed delight at President Sacasa’s activities and
                            promised fullest Costa Rican cooperation. Repeated to Managua.</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Sack</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>